ly welcomed and valued. Schools should actively highlight successful women and minorities in science and technology. Teachers need training to recognize their own biases and how they might unconsciously communicate lower expectations. We should celebrate diverse role models—not just Marie Curie, though she's wonderful, but contemporary women scientists and engineers who look like the students sitting in those classrooms. I've seen how social media, which I use quite a bit, can either reinforce stereotypes or challenge them. When I see posts celebrating young women's scientific achievements, I share them enthusiastically. We older generations have a responsibility to change the narrative. Mentorship programs pairing experienced professionals with young people from underrepresented groups can make an enormous difference. When a young woman sees someone who looks like her succeeding in STEM, it becomes real and possible. We must also ensure that our institutions—universities, workplaces, research centers—actively work to create inclusive cultures where everyone belongs. Stereotype threat is real, measurable, and preventable. With intention and compassion, we can build a future where talent flourishes regardless of gender or background.","reasoning_summary":"The persona is a 74-year-old retired Italian woman with low openness but high extraversion and agreeableness, suggesting she values personal connection and tradition while being socially engaged. Her father's PhD indicates exposure to academic thinking despite her own lower secondary education. High conscientiousness supports careful consideration of solutions. Her daily social media use and warm personality inform her perspective on communication and mentorship. Her Christian faith and Italian background suggest values of community and human dignity. The response draws on her life experience, her concern for younger generations (she has one child), and her ability to connect emotionally with others while advocating